## What
Implement the local HTTP + WebSocket server in cli/server.ts.

## Architecture
```typescript
import express from 'express';
import { createServer } from 'http';
import { WebSocketServer, WebSocket } from 'ws';

const app = express();
const httpServer = createServer(app);
const wss = new WebSocketServer({ server: httpServer });

// Loopback-only security — reject non-local connections at upgrade time
httpServer.on('upgrade', (req, socket, head) => {
  const addr = req.socket.remoteAddress;
  const isLocal = addr === '127.0.0.1' || addr === '::1' || addr === '::ffff:127.0.0.1';
  if (!isLocal) { socket.write('HTTP/1.1 403 Forbidden

'); socket.destroy(); return; }
  wss.handleUpgrade(req, socket, head, ws => wss.emit('connection', ws, req));
});
```

## Static Dashboard Serving
```typescript
app.use('/dashboard', express.static(resolve(__dirname, '../dashboard/dist')));
app.get('/', (_, res) => res.redirect('/dashboard'));
```

## WebSocket Heartbeat (mandatory)
```typescript
const heartbeat = setInterval(() => {
  wss.clients.forEach((ws: AliveWS) => {
    if (!ws.isAlive) { ws.terminate(); return; }
    ws.isAlive = false;
    ws.ping();
  });
}, 30_000);
wss.on('close', () => clearInterval(heartbeat));
```

Without heartbeat, dead browser tabs accumulate in wss.clients forever (memory leak).

## Acceptance criteria
- Server starts on localhost:4200
- Non-loopback WebSocket connections terminated at upgrade (before handshake completes)
- Heartbeat interval prevents dead client accumulation
- Static dashboard served from /dashboard path

## What
Implement the server-side polling loops that pull data from VPS and push to WebSocket clients.

## Polling Architecture
Three independent setInterval loops, each with its own error handling:

```typescript
// Agent snapshot (10s)
const snapshotLoop = setInterval(async () => {
  try {
    const snapshot = await ntm.snapshot();
    // Save to bead_snapshots table (for velocity ETA)
    beadSnapshots.insert(runId, snapshot);
    // Push to all WS clients
    broadcast({ type: 'snapshot', data: snapshot, ts: Date.now() });
  } catch (err) {
    broadcast({ type: 'error', message: String(err) });
  }
}, 10_000);

// Beads (20s)
const beadsLoop = setInterval(async () => {
  try {
    const stats = await ntm.beadsStats();
    broadcast({ type: 'beads', data: stats, ts: Date.now() });
  } catch { /* br not available = no beads yet, silent */ }
}, 20_000);

// VPS health (45s)
const healthLoop = setInterval(async () => {
  const result = await ssh.exec("uptime | awk '{print $NF}' && df -h / | awk 'NR==2{print $5}'");
  const [load, diskPct] = result.stdout.split('
');
  broadcast({ type: 'vps_health', load: parseFloat(load), disk_pct: parseFloat(diskPct), ts: Date.now() });
}, 45_000);
```

## Cleanup
```typescript
process.on('SIGTERM', () => {
  clearInterval(snapshotLoop);
  clearInterval(beadsLoop);
  clearInterval(healthLoop);
});
```

## Acceptance criteria
- Each loop has independent try/catch (one failing doesn't kill others)
- bead_snapshots table populated every 20s during active run
- VPS health check uses minimal SSH exec (one command, two parsed values)
- All intervals cleared on SIGTERM

## What
WebSocket mutation handling and the two user-facing server commands.

## Mutation Handlers
The WebSocket accepts exactly 3 action types:
```typescript
wss.on('connection', (ws) => {
  ws.on('message', async (raw) => {
    const msg = JSON.parse(raw.toString()) as ClientMessage;
    switch (msg.action) {
      case 'prompt_send':
        await promptEngine.send(msg.name, msg.target, msg.vars);
        break;
      case 'swarm_pause':
        await ntm.pause(currentSession);
        eventLog.append(runId, 'swarm_pause', Phase.SWARM, Phase.SWARM, 'dashboard', {});
        break;
      case 'swarm_resume':
        await ntm.resume(currentSession);
        eventLog.append(runId, 'swarm_resume', Phase.SWARM, Phase.SWARM, 'dashboard', {});
        break;
      case 'gate_advance':
        gate.advance(runId, 'dashboard');
        break;
      default:
        ws.send(JSON.stringify({ type: 'error', message: `Unknown action: ${msg.action}` }));
    }
  });
});
```

## flywheel serve
Start the server + open browser:
```typescript
httpServer.listen(4200, '127.0.0.1', () => {
  console.log('Dashboard: http://localhost:4200/dashboard');
  open('http://localhost:4200/dashboard');  // 'open' npm package
});
```

## flywheel monitor (text mode)
For terminals without browser:
```
flywheel monitor
```
Polls ntm.markdown() every 10s and prints to stdout. Good for SSH sessions where you can't open a browser.

## Acceptance criteria
- Unknown action returns error message to sender (not crash)
- gate_advance mutation recorded with actor='dashboard'
- flywheel serve opens browser automatically (configurable with --no-open)
- flywheel monitor exits cleanly on Ctrl+C (SIGINT)

## What
Implement the full PromptEngine class in cli/prompt-engine.ts.

## Class
```typescript
export class PromptEngine {
  constructor(
    private prompts: Record<string, Prompt>,
    private db: Database.Database,
    private ntm: NtmBridge,
    private runId?: number,  // current flywheel run (for context vars)
  ) {}

  resolve(name: string, vars?: Record<string, string>): string {
    const prompt = this.prompts[name];
    if (!prompt) throw new Error(`Unknown prompt: ${name}. Run: flywheel prompts list`);

    // Build variable context: explicit > run context > ssh config
    const context = {
      ...this.getRunContext(),
      ...vars,
    };

    return interpolatePrompt(prompt.text, context);
  }

  async send(
    name: string,
    target: SendTarget,
    vars?: Record<string, string>
  ): Promise<NtmSendResult> {
    const text = this.resolve(name, vars);
    const result = await this.ntm.send(target.session, text, target);

    // Audit log
    promptSendLog.record({
      promptName: name,
      agentTarget: JSON.stringify(target),
      sentAt: new Date().toISOString(),
      runId: this.runId,
    });

    return result;
  }

  list(filter?: { phase?: string }): Prompt[] {
    return Object.entries(this.prompts)
      .filter(([, p]) => !filter?.phase || p.phase === filter.phase)
      .map(([name, p]) => ({ name, ...p }));
  }
}
```

## Variable Context Priority
1. explicit vars param (highest)
2. run context from SQLite (project_name, plan_path, phase)
3. ssh.yaml config (remote_repo_root, host)

## Acceptance criteria
- resolve() throws on unknown prompt name (with list hint)
- resolve() throws on missing variable (with variable name)
- send() always logs to prompt_sends table
- list() groups by phase correctly

## What
Implement the core ntmRobot<T>() function that all NTM bridge methods use.

## Implementation
```typescript
async function ntmRobot<T>(
  ssh: SSHManager,
  args: string[],
  opts?: { cwd?: string; timeout?: number }
): Promise<T> {
  const cmd = `ntm ${args.join(' ')}`;
  const result = await ssh.exec(cmd, { timeout: opts?.timeout ?? 10_000, cwd: opts?.cwd });

  if (result.code !== 0) {
    throw new Error(`ntm ${args[0]} failed (exit ${result.code}): ${result.stderr}`);
  }

  // NTM may emit log lines before/after JSON — extract robustly
  const raw = result.stdout;
  const match = raw.match(/(\{[\s\S]*\}|\[[\s\S]*\])/);
  if (!match) throw new Error(`No JSON in ntm output: ${raw.slice(0, 200)}`);

  return JSON.parse(match[1]) as T;
}
```

## Why the JSON Extraction Guard
NTM v1.2.0 sometimes emits internal log lines before the JSON blob. Naive JSON.parse(stdout) will throw on these. The regex extracts only the outermost JSON object or array.

## bash -lc in SSHManager.exec()
This is already handled by the bash -lc wrapper in SSHManager.exec(). ntmRobot does NOT need to add it again — it just passes the ntm command string.

## Acceptance criteria
- ntmRobot<NtmSnapshot>(ssh, ['--robot-snapshot']) returns typed snapshot
- Malformed JSON from NTM throws with first 200 chars of raw output in error
- Non-zero exit code throws with stderr content

## What
Implement the two primary polling methods on NtmBridge class.

## NtmBridge class skeleton
