- status() returns typed NtmStatus with summary counts
- Both methods use ntmRobot() base wrapper (not raw ssh.exec)

## What
Implement send() for broadcasting prompts to agents via --robot-send.

## NTM Send API (from live VPS output)
Command: ntm --robot-send <session> --msg="<text>" [--all] [--panes=X,Y] [--type=claude]
Returns: { session, sent_at, targets[], successful[], failed[{pane, error}], message_preview }

## Implementation
```typescript
async send(
  session: string,
  msg: string,
  target: { all?: boolean; pane?: string; type?: 'claude' | 'codex' | 'gemini' }
): Promise<NtmSendResult> {
  const args = ['--robot-send', session, `--msg=${JSON.stringify(msg)}`];
  if (target.all) args.push('--all');
  if (target.pane) args.push(`--panes=${target.pane}`);
  if (target.type) args.push(`--type=${target.type}`);

  return ntmRobot<NtmSendResult>(this.ssh, args);
}
```

## Acceptance criteria
- send() with {all: true} sends to all panes and returns successful[] list
- Partial failures (some panes succeed, some fail) are returned in failed[] not thrown
- Message is JSON-escaped to handle quotes, newlines, special chars

## What
Implement spawn() for creating new NTM sessions with agent presets.

## Available Recipes (from live VPS --robot-recipes output)
- quick-claude: 2 Claude agents
- full-stack: 3 Claude + 2 Codex + 1 Gemini
- minimal: 1 Claude
- codex-heavy: 4 Codex + 1 Claude
- balanced: 2 of each
- review-team: 1 Codex writer + 2 Claude reviewers

## Custom Spawn (no recipe)
flywheel swarm 4 should spawn exactly 4 Claude agents. Use:
  ntm --robot-spawn <session> --spawn-cc=4

## Implementation
```typescript
async spawn(
  session: string,
  opts: { recipe?: string; cc?: number; cod?: number; gmi?: number }
): Promise<void> {
  const args = ['--robot-spawn', session];
  if (opts.recipe) args.push(`--spawn-preset=${opts.recipe}`);
  if (opts.cc) args.push(`--spawn-cc=${opts.cc}`);
  if (opts.cod) args.push(`--spawn-cod=${opts.cod}`);
  if (opts.gmi) args.push(`--spawn-gmi=${opts.gmi}`);
  args.push('--spawn-wait');  // wait for agents to be ready
  await ntmRobot(this.ssh, args);
}
```

## Acceptance criteria
- spawn('flywheel-swarm', {cc: 4}) creates 4 Claude agents
- --spawn-wait is always used (don't send prompts to agents not ready yet)
- Session name is validated: alphanumeric + hyphens only

## What
Implement the remaining NtmBridge methods.

## pause() / resume()
NTM pause/resume sends Ctrl+C / restart signal to all agents in session.
These are the only swarm-level controls (besides send()).
```typescript
async pause(session: string): Promise<void> {
  await this.ssh.exec(`ntm --robot-interrupt ${session}`);
}
async resume(session: string): Promise<void> {
  // resume by sending empty prompt that re-engages the agent
  await this.send(session, '', {all: true});
}
```

## beadsList() — br list --json over SSH
```typescript
async beadsList(filter?: 'ready' | 'blocked' | 'all'): Promise<Bead[]> {
  const args = filter === 'ready' ? 'ready' : filter === 'blocked' ? 'blocked' : 'list';
  const result = await this.ssh.exec(`br ${args} --json`, { cwd: this.projectDir });
  if (result.stdout.includes('no .beads/ directory')) return [];  // graceful degradation
  return JSON.parse(result.stdout) as Bead[];
}
```

## beadsStats() — br stats --json
```typescript
async beadsStats(): Promise<BeadStats> {
  const result = await this.ssh.exec('br stats --json', { cwd: this.projectDir });
  return JSON.parse(result.stdout) as BeadStats;
}
```

## Acceptance criteria
- beadsList() returns [] when no .beads/ directory (VPS may not have beads initialized)
- beadsStats() handles missing br gracefully (preflight check covers this)
- pause()/resume() log to phase_events table

## What
Implement the SSHManager class in cli/ssh.ts — the single persistent SSH connection to the VPS.

## Implementation
```typescript
import { NodeSSH } from 'node-ssh';

export class SSHManager {
  private conn = new NodeSSH();
  private cfg: SSHConfig | null = null;

  async connect(cfg: SSHConfig): Promise<void> {
    this.cfg = cfg;
    await this.conn.connect({
      host: cfg.host,
      username: cfg.user,
      port: cfg.port,
      privateKeyPath: cfg.keyPath,
      keepaliveInterval: 10_000,  // critical: prevents NAT timeout killing idle connection
      keepaliveCountMax: 3,       // terminate after 3 missed keepalive replies
      readyTimeout: 30_000,
    });
  }

  isConnected(): boolean { return this.conn.isConnected(); }
  dispose(): void { this.conn.dispose(); }
}
export const sshManager = new SSHManager(); // singleton
```

## Why keepalive matters
SSH connections over NAT/firewall silently die after 5-15min idle. Without keepaliveInterval, the connection looks alive locally but is dead at the network layer. The next command hangs forever. 10s interval + 3 missed = 30s to detect dead connection.

## Why singleton
All CLI commands share one connection. No handshake per command. The `sshManager` singleton is imported by commands and the server alike.

## Acceptance criteria
- connect() throws with clear message if host unreachable
- isConnected() returns false after dispose()
- keepaliveInterval=10000 is set (verify with verbose SSH log)
- keyPath supports ~ expansion (use os.homedir())

## What
SSH onStdout/onStderr callbacks receive arbitrary Buffer chunks — NOT line-aligned. A chunk may contain 3 full lines or half a line. LineBuffer fixes this.

## Implementation
```typescript
export class LineBuffer {
  private buf = '';

  push(chunk: Buffer, cb: (line: string) => void): void {
    this.buf += chunk.toString('utf8');
    const lines = this.buf.split('\n');
    this.buf = lines.pop()!;  // incomplete trailing segment, keep buffered
    for (const line of lines) cb(line);
  }

  flush(cb: (line: string) => void): void {
    if (this.buf) { cb(this.buf); this.buf = ''; }
    this.buf = '';
  }
}
```

## Why This Matters
Without LineBuffer:
- A single `console.log(chunk)` produces garbled partial lines
- JSON parsing of streamed NTM output fails unpredictably
- Log display in the dashboard shows split lines

## Where It's Used
- SSHManager.stream() — every streaming SSH command
- NTM bridge — parsing --robot-tail output
- Server polling loop — piping stdout to WebSocket

## Acceptance criteria
- Handles chunks split mid-character (UTF-8 multibyte)
- flush() emits any remaining partial line on stream end
- Zero external dependencies

## What
Implement exec() on SSHManager — the one-shot command runner that captures all output and returns a typed result.

## Implementation
```typescript
async exec(cmd: string, opts?: { timeout?: number; cwd?: string }): Promise<ExecResult> {
  if (!this.isConnected()) throw new Error('SSH not connected. Run: flywheel ssh test');

  const wrapped = `bash -lc ${JSON.stringify(cmd)}`;  // critical: loads ~/.profile, gets PATH
  const start = Date.now();

  const result = await this.conn.execCommand(wrapped, {
    cwd: opts?.cwd,
  });

  return {
    stdout: result.stdout,
    stderr: result.stderr,
    code: result.code ?? -1,
    elapsed: Date.now() - start,
  };
}
```

## The bash -lc Pattern (CRITICAL)
Non-interactive SSH sessions do NOT source ~/.zshrc or ~/.bashrc. Tools like ntm, br, bv live in ~/.local/bin which is only on PATH in interactive sessions. Using `bash -lc` forces a login shell which sources ~/.profile and gets the full PATH.

Without this, EVERY tool call fails silently with "command not found" and the error message is buried in stderr.

## Timeout
For long-running commands, wrap with Promise.race + AbortController. For short commands (status checks), 10s default timeout is sufficient.

## Acceptance criteria
- `exec('ntm --robot-version')` returns valid JSON in stdout
- `exec('false')` returns code=1, not code=0
- elapsed is measured accurately (within 50ms)
- isConnected() guard throws before attempting exec

## What
Implement stream() on SSHManager for long-running commands that produce continuous output (log tailing, agent watching).

## Implementation
```typescript
async stream(
  cmd: string,
  onLine: (line: string, stream: 'out' | 'err') => void,
  signal: AbortSignal,
  opts?: { cwd?: string }
): Promise<void> {
  if (!this.isConnected()) throw new Error('SSH not connected');

  const wrapped = `bash -lc ${JSON.stringify(cmd)}`;
  const outBuf = new LineBuffer();
  const errBuf = new LineBuffer();

  // node-ssh exec with streaming callbacks
  const execPromise = this.conn.exec(wrapped, [], {
    cwd: opts?.cwd,
    onStdout: (chunk) => outBuf.push(chunk, (line) => onLine(line, 'out')),
    onStderr: (chunk) => errBuf.push(chunk, (line) => onLine(line, 'err')),
    stream: 'both',
  });

  // Abort: close SSH channel when signal fires
  const abortHandler = () => { /* close channel */ };
  signal.addEventListener('abort', abortHandler, { once: true });

  try {
    await execPromise;
    outBuf.flush((l) => onLine(l, 'out'));
    errBuf.flush((l) => onLine(l, 'err'));
  } finally {
    signal.removeEventListener('abort', abortHandler);
  }
}
```

## Primary Use Case
The server polling loop calls stream() for log tailing. The AbortSignal lets the server cancel tailing cleanly when the session ends or poll cycle resets.

## Acceptance criteria
- Cancels cleanly when signal.abort() is called
- flush() is called on normal stream end
- onLine called with correct 'out'/'err' stream discriminator

## What
Every command that touches the VPS must check isConnected() before proceeding and fail with a clear, actionable error message. This is a cross-cutting concern.

## Implementation
```typescript
export function requireSSH(ssh: SSHManager): void {
  if (!ssh.isConnected()) {
    console.error(chalk.red('✗ Not connected to VPS'));
    console.error(chalk.dim('  Run: flywheel ssh test'));
    process.exit(1);
  }
}
```

Apply at the top of every command action handler that uses SSH.

## Why "Loud Failure" Is A Design Principle
Auto-reconnect sounds nice but:
1. Hides the fact that something went wrong (network drop, VPS crash)
2. Introduces race conditions if reconnect is slow and commands queue
3. Makes the system harder to reason about

The VPS is autonomous — agents keep running whether or not we're connected. Loud failure + manual reconnect keeps the human in the loop about the connection state.

## Acceptance criteria
- Clear error message with exact remediation command
- process.exit(1) is called (not throw — commander catches throws silently)
- Applied consistently across ALL commands touching SSH

## What
Implement callModel() — a unified async function that takes a ModelSlot config and calls the appropriate SDK.

## Interface
```typescript
interface CallModelOpts {
  onChunk?: (text: string) => void;  // streaming progress
  signal?: AbortSignal;
}

async function callModel(
  slot: ModelSlot,
  prompt: string,
  opts?: CallModelOpts
): Promise<{ text: string; inputTokens: number; outputTokens: number }>
```

## Anthropic Implementation
```typescript
