## What
Two foundational React hooks for WebSocket connectivity.

## useWebSocket()
```typescript
export function useWebSocket(url: string, onMessage: (data: string) => void) {
  const wsRef = useRef<WebSocket | null>(null);
  const [status, setStatus] = useState<'connecting'|'open'|'closed'|'error'>('connecting');
  const reconnectTimer = useRef<ReturnType<typeof setTimeout>>();
  const backoff = useRef(1000);

  const connect = useCallback(() => {
    const ws = new WebSocket(url);
    ws.onopen = () => { setStatus('open'); backoff.current = 1000; };
    ws.onmessage = e => onMessage(e.data as string);
    ws.onerror = () => setStatus('error');
    ws.onclose = () => {
      setStatus('closed');
      reconnectTimer.current = setTimeout(() => {
        backoff.current = Math.min(backoff.current * 2, 30_000);
        connect();
      }, backoff.current);
    };
    wsRef.current = ws;
  }, [url, onMessage]);

  useEffect(() => { connect(); return () => { clearTimeout(reconnectTimer.current); wsRef.current?.close(); }; }, [connect]);
  return { status };
}
```

Exponential backoff: starts at 1s, doubles each reconnect, caps at 30s.

## useSessionFeed()
```typescript
const MAX_LINES = 1000;

export function useSessionFeed(session: string) {
  const [lines, setLines] = useState<string[]>([]);
  const [snapshot, setSnapshot] = useState<NtmSnapshot | null>(null);

  const onMessage = useCallback((raw: string) => {
    const msg = JSON.parse(raw) as ServerMessage;
    if (msg.type === 'stdout' && msg.session === session) {
      setLines(prev => {
        const next = [...prev, msg.data];
        return next.length > MAX_LINES ? next.slice(-MAX_LINES) : next;
      });
    }
    if (msg.type === 'snapshot') setSnapshot(msg.data);
  }, [session]);

  const { status } = useWebSocket('/ws', onMessage);
  return { lines, snapshot, wsStatus: status };
}
```

## Why MAX_LINES = 1000
Without a cap, a 6-hour swarm session with 5 agents generates ~100k+ log lines → browser tab crashes. 1000 lines covers ~3-5 minutes of context which is enough for monitoring.

## Acceptance criteria
- useWebSocket reconnects with exponential backoff (1s → 2s → 4s → ... → 30s)
- useSessionFeed caps at 1000 lines (older lines dropped, newest kept)
- status indicator shows 'connecting'/'open'/'closed'/'error'

## What
Implement initDb() in cli/state.ts. This is called at startup by every command that needs persistence.

## Implementation
```typescript
import Database from 'better-sqlite3';
import { homedir } from 'os';
import { mkdirSync } from 'fs';
import { resolve } from 'path';

export function initDb(path?: string): Database.Database {
  const dbPath = path ?? resolve(homedir(), '.flywheel', 'flywheel.db');
  mkdirSync(resolve(dbPath, '..'), { recursive: true });

  const db = new Database(dbPath);

  // WAL MUST be set before any reads or writes
  db.pragma('journal_mode = WAL');
  db.pragma('synchronous = NORMAL');  // safe with WAL, much faster than FULL
  db.pragma('foreign_keys = ON');
  db.pragma('cache_size = -32000');   // 32MB cache

  db.exec(SCHEMA);  // existing SCHEMA constant — CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS is idempotent
  return db;
}
```

## Why WAL Mode Is Non-Negotiable
Default journal_mode (DELETE) means writers block readers and readers block writers. With WAL:
- The polling server can write bead_snapshots while a CLI command reads phase_events
- No deadlocks between the long-running server and short-lived CLI invocations

## Idempotency
All CREATE TABLE statements in SCHEMA already use IF NOT EXISTS. initDb() is safe to call multiple times — upgrading from an existing DB just runs no-ops.

